WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.520
[Music]

00:00:05.520 --> 00:00:14.160
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. This is a series&nbsp;
on the foundations of mathematics where I attempt&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:23.120
to set up a somewhat new and better foundation&nbsp;
for the subject. It's a very ambitious program,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:29.280
and we've just begun the subject. We've talked&nbsp;
about arithmetic and some sort of elementary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:33.680
aspects of how to set that up. We've talked&nbsp;
about geometry and some elementary aspects&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:39.280
of how to set that up. Now it's time to&nbsp;
go to the third most important aspect of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:46.560
the subject. Mathematics has three key&nbsp;
areas: arithmetic is the primary one;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:52.160
it's the most important and historically the&nbsp;
oldest. Geometry is the second most important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.160 --> 00:00:58.480
and the second oldest, and the third most&nbsp;
important and the third oldest is algebra.

00:00:58.480 --> 00:01:02.960
So today we're going to initiate our discussion&nbsp;
of algebra, and we're going to have quite a lot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:02.960 --> 00:01:08.320
to say about algebra. It's a very rich subject,&nbsp;
and I think a lot of what we're going to say also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:15.760
impacts primary school education and high school&nbsp;
education too. As you will see, we'll also have a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:25.400
chance to see how to look at some very standard&nbsp;
things in a new light, perhaps a better light.

00:01:25.400 --> 00:01:32.120
So let's start by positioning this subject roughly&nbsp;
in terms of arithmetic and geometry. I think of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:32.120 --> 00:01:39.000
algebra as forming a bridge between arithmetic&nbsp;
and geometry. It emanates from arithmetic and ties&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:46.440
these two fundamental disciplines together. If I&nbsp;
had to say what algebra was in a single sentence,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:53.120
perhaps simplified, I would say something like&nbsp;
algebra is generalized arithmetic. We take the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:53.120 --> 00:01:59.280
arithmetic that we've been studying—just&nbsp;
arithmetic with natural numbers, integers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:05.160
fractions, rational numbers, the basic&nbsp;
arithmetic involving the operations of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:12.400
addition, multiplication, subtraction,&nbsp;
and division—and then we look to extend&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.400 --> 00:02:17.920
those operations and those numbers.&nbsp;
We're going to enlarge our idea of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:17.920 --> 00:02:25.400
objects that we can do arithmetic with, and&nbsp;
that's basically how algebra comes about.

00:02:25.400 --> 00:02:31.320
Historically, its origins probably go back to the&nbsp;
Babylonians, but the Greeks already had a pretty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:38.280
good idea of algebra in a geometrical context. As&nbsp;
I've already discussed in the talks about Greek&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:38.280 --> 00:02:44.600
geometry, Euclid had a kind of geometrical&nbsp;
algebra where algebraic expressions were&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:44.600 --> 00:02:52.400
interpreted and proven geometrically. Somewhat&nbsp;
later, Nicomachus wrote an influential book&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:52.400 --> 00:02:59.280
called "Introductio Arithmetica," in which&nbsp;
he emphasized the importance of arithmetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:06.240
essentially aside from geometry, not necessarily&nbsp;
built up from geometry. The greatest arithmetician&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:12.880
of the Greek times was Diophantus, who lived&nbsp;
250 years after Christ and whose name gives&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:18.640
us the subject of Diophantine equations, which&nbsp;
are equations where we're looking for solutions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:18.640 --> 00:03:25.520
purely in terms of integers or sometimes&nbsp;
rational numbers. He wrote a book called&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:31.040
"Arithmetica," actually 13 books together—I think&nbsp;
some of them have been lost—but nevertheless he&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:31.040 --> 00:03:38.200
gives us a very thorough treatment of a lot of&nbsp;
different problems, somewhat unrelated perhaps,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:38.200 --> 00:03:45.400
and not a lot of systematic theory, but he's able&nbsp;
to solve a lot of interesting problems, such as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:45.400 --> 00:03:55.480
this one here: find three numbers such that their&nbsp;
sum and the sum of any two of them is a square.

00:03:55.480 --> 00:04:01.400
But algebra as a separate discipline&nbsp;
from arithmetic really only gets going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:01.400 --> 00:04:07.000
with the Hindus and then later the Arabs.&nbsp;
So let's have a look at that development.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:12.000
Earlier in this series, we've already remarked&nbsp;
that Hindu mathematics was notable for their&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:18.560
introduction of essentially our numerical system.&nbsp;
The decimal number system that we use to represent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:18.560 --> 00:04:26.160
numbers is basically a gift to us from the Hindu&nbsp;
mathematicians and a crucially important one. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:31.840
given their very strong foundation arithmetically,&nbsp;
it's no surprise that they were able to solve a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:31.840 --> 00:04:38.040
lot of reasonably sophisticated algebraic&nbsp;
problems. Some names that are notable are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.040 --> 00:04:49.800
Aryabhata, who lived around 400 AD, Brahmagupta&nbsp;
around 600 AD, and Bhaskara in the 12th century.

00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:55.760
Aspects of this Hindu arithmetic algebra&nbsp;
include, first of all, a richer numerical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:55.760 --> 00:05:01.800
system which was quite comfortable with&nbsp;
working with fractional, negative numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.800 --> 00:05:08.160
and also irrational numbers like square roots&nbsp;
of natural numbers—square root of 3, square root&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.160 --> 00:05:13.000
of 5, and so on. They were very familiar with&nbsp;
quadratic equations and how to solve a quadratic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:19.040
equation and more sophisticated things too. A very&nbsp;
important number theoretical Diophantine equation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:24.560
called Pell's equation nowadays, which&nbsp;
goes back much earlier to even Archimedes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:32.920
is x^2 - 61y^2 = 1. If you try to solve that&nbsp;
equation for integers x and y, then aside&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:32.920 --> 00:05:38.920
from the sort of trivial solution 1, you'll be&nbsp;
challenged to find a solution if you don't know&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:38.920 --> 00:05:46.440
some of the theory that the Hindu mathematicians&nbsp;
and subsequent generations discovered.

00:05:46.440 --> 00:05:52.520
After the Hindus, the torch passed to the Arab&nbsp;
mathematicians, who took the Hindu works, took the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.520 --> 00:05:59.320
Greek works, studied them both, put them together,&nbsp;
and developed them further. The name of algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:04.880
in fact, comes from the work of Muhammad ibn&nbsp;
Musa al-Khwarizmi (not sure if I'm pronouncing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:11.240
that right) around 800 AD, who wrote a book called&nbsp;
in Arabic "Al-Kitab al-Mukhtasar fi Hisab al-Jabr&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.240 --> 00:06:15.200
wal-Muqabala," which roughly means "The&nbsp;
Compendious Book on Calculation by Completion&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:21.680
and Balancing." The kinds of things that he was&nbsp;
referring to with "completion" is this process:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:21.680 --> 00:06:28.280
say you have an equation x^2 - 3 = 13, where&nbsp;
x is an unknown number that you're trying to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.280 --> 00:06:33.920
determine. Then what you can do is you can&nbsp;
take the -3 away from the left-hand side&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:39.280
and you can restore it by essentially taking&nbsp;
it away from the right-hand side or adding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:39.280 --> 00:06:45.160
it to the right-hand side. This is a very&nbsp;
typical kind of basic operation in algebra.

00:06:45.160 --> 00:06:49.840
Other mathematicians, like Omar Khayyam&nbsp;
around 1100, who was notable for being&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:49.840 --> 00:06:55.920
a literary great as well (he wrote&nbsp;
the Rubaiyat), were very interested&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:55.920 --> 00:07:01.760
in cubic equations and showed how to solve&nbsp;
certain cubic equations using conic sections.

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:08.760
Alright, so with that very brief historical&nbsp;
introduction, what happens in algebra? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:13.200
one of the key ideas certainly is that we're&nbsp;
going to use letters instead of numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:13.200 --> 00:07:21.040
or letters together with numbers. This has&nbsp;
a lot of advantages and it allows general&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:21.040 --> 00:07:27.400
laws to be more easily stated—something that&nbsp;
we've already done so far. It often clarifies&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:27.400 --> 00:07:34.960
the essentials of a problem in that you get to&nbsp;
see the wood, not just the trees. It leads to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:39.160
various higher arithmetics, especially&nbsp;
related to things called polynomials,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:39.160 --> 00:07:43.680
which are going to play an important role in&nbsp;
algebra. And it shows the connections between&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:50.240
different kinds of questions—that certain kinds&nbsp;
of questions are actually very much the same.

00:07:50.240 --> 00:07:55.840
But a natural question that bedevils a&nbsp;
lot of first-time learners of algebra is:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:55.840 --> 00:08:02.240
what do these letters actually mean? What is&nbsp;
x? What is y? And that's something that we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:02.240 --> 00:08:09.080
going to talk about. It turns out that it's&nbsp;
not so simple to say what those things are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:09.080 --> 00:08:16.040
because the nature of the x's and y's and z's&nbsp;
and so on that appear in algebra changes as you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:16.040 --> 00:08:20.920
become a little bit more sophisticated.&nbsp;
When you start off with the subject, x,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:26.360
y, and z have a certain role and a certain&nbsp;
meaning, but later on, that meaning changes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.360 --> 00:08:31.360
in quite a different direction. And so there's&nbsp;
a subtle but important shift that we're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:35.080
to have to pay attention to because we're&nbsp;
interested in what's really going on and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:35.080 --> 00:08:41.760
being precise about the basic structures and&nbsp;
the basic objects that we're going to be using.

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:47.680
Okay, so we're going to roughly follow&nbsp;
a program like this: to start off with,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:47.680 --> 00:08:50.800
first we're going to talk about&nbsp;
what we might call Baby Algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:50.800 --> 00:08:57.320
which is more or less arithmetic with letters.&nbsp;
Then we're going to move on to polynomials,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:57.320 --> 00:09:02.200
and I'm going to introduce things called poly&nbsp;
numbers, which are very closely related to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:07.640
polynomials but have some interesting advantages.&nbsp;
We're going to talk about rational functions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:07.640 --> 00:09:13.000
which are a very important field of doing&nbsp;
arithmetic, and we're going to talk about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:18.200
matrices, which is another extension of&nbsp;
arithmetic. And of course, algebra has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:18.200 --> 00:09:25.600
much more in it, but probably this will be good&nbsp;
for a first stab at what the subject is about.

00:09:25.600 --> 00:09:29.760
So next time we are going&nbsp;
to start with Baby Algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:32.360
the algebra that students&nbsp;
learn when they're 10, 11,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:32.360 --> 00:09:45.320
12 years old. I hope you'll join me for that.&nbsp;
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:09:45.320 --> 00:09:46.320
[Music]

